reviews.text: Beautiful place to visit. One of the best displayed Museums I've seen. Manageable size and friendly knowledgeable volunteers. You can avoid the Holocaust section.  Interesting even if not interested! Nice cafe too.

Such a brilliant museum. Gives a brief introduction to the faith. The main part of the museum gives a brilliant insight into the stories and history of Jewish people in Britain, from the Normon conquest to modern day. There is a brilliant balance between the general history and personal experiences. It taught me so much I never knew. Also visited the exhibition "Jews, Money, Myth". So, so interesting and insightful! Wonderfully curated. There was printed texts on the walls of a conversation between the director and curator, giving insight into the reasons for what was exhibited and what was not and the reasons why. I would definitely recommend.

Good insight into Jewish history. Very large section on London history some of which is good some of which is terrible (suffering, poverty) - reflected well. As to whether to immerse yourself? Wait till they have exhibition or a peculiar on So you get to see one more floor
A well appointed museum that is easy to see in 4 hours. The displays are well lit and the descriptions easily read. Well worth the visit
Nice and interesting museum full of Jewish and Israeli history and even more.  Small cafe for a quick lunch. Would recommend it as Camden Market very near by. Wish the ticket price was lower..

Very small museum, cool knowledgeable guides that seem to master a lot of the countrie's historic, traditional and mythological stories. In an hour you can see most part of it. There is a little shop outside of the museum where you can buy some artifacts that are also available elsewhere at lesser price.
I like this place but I would love it if it had enough traditional and local object. I think it doesn't represent enough the national heritage

I loved visiting this museum. I wish I could've taken pictures. Nevertheless, our tour guide, William Dayo, was very well versed in each of the exhibits. It was really nice to have someone with us who gave us in depth information on what we were viewing. It gave us a deeper understanding and appreciation for each of the artifacts.
It was nice. The museum has a lot to offer in cultural history and I was happy to see them opened on a Sunday.

This museum continues the tradition of equating Western African culture and history mainly with masks (sarcasm). It could almost be interchangeable with the museum's in Dakar and Bamako except they both have a second floor dedicated to textiles. 

Granted, the masks are interesting and high quality, but they are completely decontextualized with cryptic captions an little explanation tying anything together.

There is one table showing the evolution of money that was nice. 

It's one of the few times I wished there was a museum gift shop with some books. 

Weirdly they don't allow photography either, as if history should be hidden. 

Avoid the restaurant out back it is way overpriced and there are better maquis around.

A great place to visit with a fantastic range of interesting artifacts, pretty much something for everyone with clothing, furniture, porcelain and religious artifacts.
There are some really interesting exhibitions from time to time, especially the jewellery exhibition that is not usually my thing but I really enjoyed it.
The staff are all friendly and the exhibits are displayed really well in a way that let's you really see them up close.

It's not the first time I visit this little gem - the museum has a very well curated beautifully presented permanent exhibition of several epochs, divided by period and style, over 4 floors. Sounds big, but it's totally doable within 2 hours even.
The highlight is their vast fashion collection and quality furniture collection.
Eventhough I know the permanent exhibition well, I visited lately the focus exhibition on jewelry. They integrated this special exhibition, as other 3 focus changing exhibitions, into the permanent one, so you don't pay any extra.
Entrance at 8€ is well invested.

This review is very subjective. I went here on a cold wednesday morning and was the only one there except for the security guards. It's huge with its four huge floors and have many different artifacts from many different era's. It did however feel very stuffy and was lacking a story. Not interactive and unless you are a person who can appreciate the workmanship of a vase, you won't enjoy it very much. Not my cup of tea.

A well curated museum in an interesting building.  If you have an interest in the decorative arts or fashion history, well worth a visit.  If it is not your area of interest, I would suggest another museum in the area.
The modern design section is very good but fairly small.  The rest we did not find that interesting
